The article discusses the progress made in the fight against AIDS and the efforts of the Obama Administration to create an AIDS-free generation. The article highlights the achievements of the President's Emergency Plan for AIDS Relief (PEPFAR), which has treated nearly four and a half million people and is on track to reach six million people by the end of 2013. The article emphasizes the need for shared responsibility among partner countries, donor nations, and multilateral organizations. The U.S. is the largest contributor to the Global Fund to Fight AIDS, Tuberculosis, and Malaria, and President Obama made a commitment of $4 billion to the fund over three years. The article also mentions the importance of faith-based organizations, civil society, and public-private partnerships in the fight against AIDS. The article concludes by stating the Obama Administration's commitment to continue efforts to save lives and build a healthier, more secure world.